postcontent:
Here's an original P17 Enfield rifle made by Eddystone in May of 1918 making it over 96 years old. 

It's in very good plus condition with at least 85% of its original blued metal finish. There is absolutely no rust, other corrosion, or pitting on the metal anywhere. 

Wood is in nice shape too without any cracks or splits. The walnut is nicely figured making it attractive. 

Numbers match and the original "US FLAMING BOMB" proof-marks are intact. 

Perhaps the best feature of this rifle is the excellent condition of it's bore. There is no pitting or rust at all, and rifling is strong. Many P17's have issues with their bores because of the corrosive ammo that was used during the time these rifles saw service. I feel quite certain the barrel is original to this rifle as the Flaming Bomb proof mark and date of manufacture (5-18) is stamped on top of it just behind the front sights.

There is also an original US P17 Bayonet included complete with leather scabbard. The Bayonet is in good condition and has the all the appropriate proof marks.

title: For Sale:  HECKLER & KOCH P7M8 ***H&K P7M8
postcontent: Heckler & Koch P7M8 is the perfect auto-loading police-use pistol. The reason it is considered ideal is due to its completely unique safety system, namely the "squeezecocker" control surface built into the front of the grip. When the operator picks up the firearm, the main shooting hand instinctually squeezes the panel rearward, and this action cocks the striker rearward while unlocking the sear for use. The panel is spring-loaded, which means when pressure is reduced, it snaps forward, decocking the striker and locking the trigger. This system is also designed to release the slide when it is locked rearward. This design eliminates the need for a decocker, external safety lever or slide stop lever, making the sides of the firearm completely flush and reducing overall width. The barrel is fixed (does not cant upwards) which means despite the firearm's compact size, it is capable of printing groups of 2 inches or less at 25 yards. This accuracy is easily comparable to many high-end automatic pistols in production. It has classic three white-dot sights dovetailed into the slide. I purchased it New in 1996 and have fired approximately 400 rounds through it without a single jam.Will include extra mags and nice holster.OREGON Residents ONLY

title: For Sale:  WARNING, SCAM: Schmidt & Bender Short Dot 1.1-4x20 NIB!
postcontent:
This is a continuing scam by a criminal trying to fraudulently sell this non-existent scope.  This scam has been posted many times and flagged and shut down many times.  Ask the supposed "seller" to provide a picture of the serial # on the scope and their original proof of purchase to prove ownership-they won't because they have neither as they stole the picture from another website and they cannot take a picture of something they do not actually have.  

The criminal is using the e-mail address "REDACTED" and their user name is "Dan Dupre", but judging from their numerous spelling errors and syntax mistakes, they are not a native English speaker.  For example, he asked me for a copy of my FFL to buy the scope...uhm, you don't need an FFL for a scope. He also balked when I requested a picture of the serial number on the scope itself and his proof of orginal purchase.  He could not provide either because - wait for it- he does not actually have the scope.

Ask them for their residence mailing address, e-mail address and phone number and ensure they all match and are consistent with one another.  You can file a local criminal case with the police if they scam you and have the police subpoena the phone company and the internet provider to determine their exact physical location (i.e. their residence) which will lead to their actual identity for prosecution.

Also, ask them for their paypal account for a money transfer as paypal protects you against fraud and acts as an escrow service.  Or, use safefunds.com, an established third party escrow service which protects both the seller and the buyer. But let me guess, the "seller" will insist on using a money order (don't ever do it) or wire transfer to a bank account (don't do it).  However, do post whatever information they give you here on Armslist to help prevent further criminal activity which undermines the purpose of this website and the mainly honest patrons who use it.
